  <static seed="88" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/SubtractFractions110.pg">
    <statement><p>Subtract: <m>\displaystyle{ 3 - \frac{19}{6}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-{\frac{1}{6}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When doing arithmetic with fractions, it helps to rewrite any integers as fractions:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 3 = \frac{3}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, to subtract a fraction, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator <m>6</m>. We will change the first fraction to have the common denominator:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{3}{1} \amp = \frac{3 \cdot 6}{1 \cdot 6}\\ \amp = \frac{18}{6} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Finally, we subtract the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   3 - \frac{19}{6}
        \amp = \frac{18}{6} - \frac{19}{6} \\
        \amp = \frac{18 - 19}{6} \\
        \amp = -\frac{1}{6}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>\displaystyle{ -\frac{1}{6}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
